Discord MCP servers are bridges that expose the Discord API as tools for AI assistants, enabling you to manage servers, channels, messages, and roles using natural language [1][2][3]. Multiple open-source implementations exist, varying in tool count and architecture, such as those by cappylab [4], PaSympa [2], and rayenking [5], which offer extensive tool suites (90+ tools) for production use cases [4][5].

To use one, install the package via npm or Docker and provide a DISCORD_TOKEN [2][5][6]. Configure your MCP client (e.g., Claude Desktop or Cursor) by adding the server to your configuration file [2][3]:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "discord": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@pasympa/discord-mcp"],
      "env": {
        "DISCORD_TOKEN": "YOUR_TOKEN"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Most servers use stdio transport and standard Discord bot permissions [4][5][6]. Reference the documentation for specific tool availability, such as message moderation, role management, or forum support [2][5][6].
